This code looks a little hard to read. Why don't we refactor in this way? 

```cpp
auto it = object_id_refs_.find(object_id);
if (it == object_id_refs_.end()) {
  RAY_LOG(DEBUG) << "Object " << object_id
                  << " not in reference table, locality data not available";
  return {}
}

const auto &node_id = it->second.pinned_at_raylet_id;
if (!node_id) {
  RAY_LOG(DEBUG)
      << "Reference " << it->second.call_site << " for object " << object_id
      << " doesn't have a defined pinned raylet ID, locality data not available";
  return {}
}

// The raylet ID to which this reference is pinned is defined.
const auto object_size = it->second.object_size;
if (object_size < 0) {
  RAY_LOG(DEBUG) << "Reference " << it->second.call_site << " for object "
                  << object_id
                  << " has an unknown object size, locality data not available";
  return {}
}

// The object size of this reference is known.
absl::optional<LocalityData> locality_data(
    {static_cast<uint64_t>(object_size), {node_id.value()}});
return locality_data;
```

This inner for loop will only be reached if the prior `if (...)` condition is true, and that [will only happen if `locality_data` contains a value](https://github.com/abseil/abseil-cpp/blob/e7ca23acac146b10edc4f752edd0bd28b0f14ea3/absl/types/optional.h#L442-L452). I've seen this `optional` pattern used and promoted elsewhere., but do you think this is too implicit? We could always opt for the more verbose
```c++
auto locality_data = locality_data_provider_->GetLocalityData(object_id);
if (locality_data.has_value()) {
    // ....
}
```

