@nfelt: When preempting back to the original step or before, I think
that it actually doesn’t have any rounding error as written.

Since `preempt` is called first in `offer`, before even incrementing
`seen`, when you preempt to step 0 we get `fac_preempted == 1.0` exactly
(since `preempted == old_stored`), and thus set `self.seen = 0`.

This test passes:

```rust
    #[test]
    fn test_preempt_long() {
        let mut rsv = StageReservoir::new(10);
        let mut head = Basin::new();
        for i in 0..100_000 {
            rsv.offer(Step(i), ());
        }
        rsv.commit(&mut head);
        // head.as_slice()[0] happens to be step 25630 here
        assert_eq!(rsv.seen, 100_000);
        rsv.offer(Step(0), ());
        assert_eq!(rsv.seen, 1); // exactly correct: just the newest record
        for i in 1..9 {
            rsv.offer(Step(i), ());
        }
        rsv.commit(&mut head);
        assert_eq!(
            head.as_slice()
                .iter()
                .map(|&(Step(s), _)| s)
                .collect::<Vec<i64>>(),
            (0..9).collect::<Vec<i64>>()
        );
        assert_eq!(rsv.seen, 9); // exactly correct: just 0 and 1..9
    }
```

Supposing that we include a test something like this, does it seem
reasonable to you to keep the code as is, without special casing for
preempting back to start?

