I didn't find that issue. It is true that string indexes start at 1 while integer_vectors start at 0 ([integer_vector_ptr_pkg-body-200x.vhd#L70](https://github.com/VUnit/vunit/blob/master/vunit/vhdl/data_types/src/integer_vector_ptr_pkg-body-200x.vhd#L70) and [string_ptr_pkg-body-200x.vhd#L74](https://github.com/VUnit/vunit/blob/master/vunit/vhdl/data_types/src/string_ptr_pkg-body-200x.vhd#L74)). But, AFAIK, that is transparent to the user (see [integer_vector_ptr_pkg-body-200x.vhd#L100](https://github.com/VUnit/vunit/blob/master/vunit/vhdl/data_types/src/integer_vector_ptr_pkg-body-200x.vhd#L100) and [string_ptr_pkg-body-200x.vhd#L104](https://github.com/VUnit/vunit/blob/master/vunit/vhdl/data_types/src/string_ptr_pkg-body-200x.vhd#L104)).

Nevertheless, I did implement an offset when an string_ptr is declared as an access and the pointer value is retrieved through VHPIDIRECT:

```
  if s.len /= 0 then --is_external
    if s.len < 0 then
      write_char(s.id, index, value);
    else
      st.eptrs(s.id)(index+1) := value;
    end if;
  else
    st.ptrs(s.id)(index) := value;
  end if;
```

As you see, when the array is of type `eptr` (external through access), the index is incremented. But with `id=0` (current main implementation) or through external functions, the offset is not required.

Apart from that, `byte_vector` is just an alias of `string`. I.e., it is possible to write/read values of type `natural` in a `string_ptr` (and are automatically converted to/from `character`). See the overloaded get, set, resize... in `string_ptr_pkg.vhd`.

Moreover, in example `external_buffer`, `byte_vector` is used instead of `string` and data is read/written to index `0` without error. See https://github.com/dbhi/vunit/blob/feat-external-arrays/examples/vhdl/external_buffer/src/test/tb_external_buffer.vhd and https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/38422348/58498696-dde2c700-817e-11e9-9bd0-d70aa2134fd9.gif

